			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="637">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Shozan Jack Haubner&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4580">A Zen Zealot Comes Home</a>&rdquo; [September 2011] is perfect. I have been meditating on and off for years, and I just came back from eighteen months volunteering in Sri Lanka. Within days of returning home I was caught in the family tangle, angry with my siblings for using bottled water and not recycling!</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Nancy Shamban<br>New York, New York</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="638">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I was relieved when Shozan Jack Haubner acknowledged the violence he inflicted on his siblings as a boy. Until that point, I&rsquo;d been thinking, <em>What about poor Helen, the sister who had sidewalk slush jammed into her nostrils, ears, and eye sockets? </em>Having been mistreated by my older brother when we were young, I would have loved nothing more than to have been rescued by our father, the way Haubner&rsquo;s father came to his sister&rsquo;s rescue. Like Haubner, my brother has never apologized. After reading the essay, I am closer to understanding why.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">D.R.<br>Bellingham, Washington</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="639">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Two passages in Shozan Jack Haubner&rsquo;s essay struck me as deeply true:</p>

<p>&ldquo;These were not the same people who raised me. Those people existed only in my head .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. while my actual parents got older, gentler, wiser.&rdquo; And &ldquo;Just because you hurt doesn&rsquo;t mean you&rsquo;re doing something wrong. It may simply mean that you&rsquo;re alive.&rdquo;</p>

<p>If it took the discomfort and angst of Thanksgiving at home with his parents to bring forth these nuggets of wisdom, it was worth it.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Libby Hewes<br>San Diego, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="640">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>As a woman in the process of leaving the religion of her childhood, I saw some of my future in Shozan Jack Haubner&rsquo;s essay. I also found the comfort of companionship in what can sometimes be a very lonely path.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jodi Kiffmeyer<br>Rice Lake, Wisconsin</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

